                "answerBody": "No. Based on available evidence, children do not appear to be at higher risk for COVID-19 than adults. While some children and infants have been sick with COVID-19, adults make up most of the known cases to date. However, a few children have developed [multisystem inflammatory syndrome (MIS-C)](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/MIS-C-Fact-Sheet.pdf). Currently, information about MIS-C is limited, and the CDC is working to learn more.\n\nYou can encourage your child to help stop the spread of COVID-19 by teaching them to do the same things everyone should do to stay healthy.\n\n*   **Stay home if you are sick** and avoid people who are sick.\n*   **Wear a cloth face mask or covering**.\n*   **Keep a 6-foot distance from others** who are not part of your household.\n*   **Wash hands often** using soap and water (or hand sanitizer with at least 60% alcohol).\n*   **Socialize with household members or other trusted households** that are also taking health and safety precautions.\n*   **Clean and disinfect high-touch surfaces daily** in household common areas (like tables, hard-backed chairs, doorknobs, light switches, remotes, handles, desks, toilets, sinks).\n*   **Wash items** including washable plush toys, according to the manufacturer’s instructions. If possible, wash items using the warmest appropriate water setting for the items and dry items completely. Dirty laundry from a person who is sick can be washed with other people’s items.\n\nVermonters can get together with friends and family, but are encouraged to keep groups small when possible to limit any possible exposure to the virus and to keep it from spreading and to follow health and safety precautions. Learn how to [safely connect with friends and family](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/Safely_Connect_with_Friends_and_Family_FINAL.pdf).\n\nFind more [resources for families with children](https://www.healthvermont.gov