            {
                "question": "Should I be tested for COVID-19?",
                "answerBody": "**Not everyone needs to be tested for COVID-19.** Use [CDC’s Self-Checker](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/testing/index.html) to find out if you should be tested. If you think you may need to get tested, talk with your health care provider, or call 2-1-1 if you don’t have a provider and need to be connected to care.\n\nIf you:\n\n*   have [**symptoms of COVID-19**](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/about-coronavirus-disease-covid-19#prevention) **–** contact your health care provider to ask about a test\n*   are in **quarantine because of travel** – contact your health care provider to ask about a test on or after day 7 of quarantine\n*   are in **quarantine because you are a** [**close contact of someone with COVID-19**](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19_What-to-do-if-you-are-a-close-contact-of-someone-with-COVID-19_final.pdf)– contact your health care provider to ask about a test on or after day 7 of quarantine\n*   need a test to **prepare for a medical procedure** – arrange a test through the health care provider who is doing your procedure\n*   have **no symptoms and are not in quarantine** – use [CDC’s Self-Checker](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/testing/index.html) to find out if you should be tested. If you do need testing, look for a clinic or pharmacy that offers testing near you, or register at a pop-up location.\n\nThere is no cost to individuals for the COVID-19 test.\n\nThe number of Vermonters who were tested for COVID-19 is updated daily on the [Current Activity in Vermont data dashboard](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/current-activity-vermont).",
                "date": "2020-08-04"
            },
            {
                "question": "Should I be tested for COVID-19?",
                "answerBody": "**Not everyone needs to be tested for COVID-19.** Use [CDC’s Self-Checker](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/testing/index.html) to find out if you should be tested. If you think you may need to get tested, talk with your health care provider. If you do not have a health care provider, call 2-1-1 to be connected to care, or contact the nearest [federally qualified health center](https://bistatepca.org/community-resources/vt-health-centers) or one of [Vermont’s free & referral clinics](https://vtfreeclinics.org/).\n\nIf you:\n\n*   have [**symptoms of COVID-19**](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/about-coronavirus-disease-covid-19#prevention) **–** contact your health care provider to ask about a test\n*   are in **quarantine because of travel** – contact your health care provider to ask about a test on or after day 7 of quarantine\n*   are in **quarantine because you are a** [**close contact of someone with COVID-19**](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19_What-to-do-if-you-are-a-close-contact-of-someone-with-COVID-19_final.pdf)– contact your health care provider to ask about a test on or after day 7 of quarantine\n*   need a test to **prepare for a medical procedure** – arrange a test through the health care provider who is doing your procedure\n*   have **no symptoms and are not in quarantine** – use [CDC’s Self-Checker](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/testing/index.html) to find out if you should be tested. If you do need testing, look for a clinic or pharmacy that offers testing near you, or register at a pop-up location.\n\nThere is no cost to individuals for the COVID-19 test.\n\nThe number of Vermonters who were tested for COVID-19 is updated daily on the [Current Activity in Vermont data dashboard](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/current-activity-vermont).",
                "date": "2020-08-07"
            },
            {
                "question": "Should I be tested for COVID-19?",
                "answerBody": "While anyone can get tested, not everyone needs to get tested. The best way to protect yourself from COVID-19 is to follow a few key [prevention tips](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/about-coronavirus-disease-covid-19#prevention). If you think you should be tested for COVID-19, talk with your health care provider. If you don't have a provider, call 2-1-1 to be connected to care, or contact the nearest [federally qualified health center](https://bistatepca.org/community-resources/vt-health-centers) or one of [Vermont's free & referral clinics](https://vtfreeclinics.org/).\n\nThe Health Department **recommends testing** for: \n\n*   People with [COVID-19 symptoms](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/symptoms-testing/symptoms.html).  \n*   People who have had [close contact](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19_What-to-do-if-you-are-a-close-contact-of-someone-with-COVID-19_final.pdf) (within 6 feet for about 15 minutes) with someone who tested positive for COVID-19.  \n*   People who are referred by their health care provider for testing for another reason.  \n\n**We do not recommend people get tested before visiting another household or attending a gathering just to make sure they're okay.** Testing only tells you if you had COVID-19 on the day you were tested. You could have already been exposed but may have been tested too early for it to show up on the test, or you could be exposed to COVID-19 after you are tested. Testing is not [prevention](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/about-coronavirus-disease-covid-19#prevention), and a negative test does not necessarily mean it is safe to gather with others. \n\n**We do not recommend people get tested frequently.** We do not recommend routine, repeated testing just for peace of mind. While testing supplies are currently in adequate supply, we need to use what we have wisely.\n\nThere is no cost to individuals for the COVID-19 test.\n\nThe number of Vermonters who were tested for COVID-19 is updated daily on the [Current Activity in Vermont data dashboard](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/current-activity-vermont).",
                "date": "2020-08-24"
            },
            {
                "question": "Should I be tested for COVID-19?",
                "answerBody": "While anyone can get tested, not everyone needs to get tested. The best way to protect yourself from COVID-19 is to follow a few key [prevention tips](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/about-coronavirus-disease-covid-19#prevention). If you think you should be tested for COVID-19, talk with your health care provider. If you don't have a provider, call 2-1-1 to be connected to care, or contact the nearest [federally qualified health center](https://bistatepca.org/community-resources/vt-health-centers) or one of [Vermont's free & referral clinics](https://vtfreeclinics.org/).\n\nThe Health Department **recommends testing** for:\n\n*   People with [COVID-19 symptoms](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/symptoms-testing/symptoms.html).\n*   People who have had [close contact](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19_What-to-do-if-you-are-a-close-contact-of-someone-with-COVID-19_final.pdf) (within 6 feet for about 15 minutes) with someone who tested positive for COVID-19.\n*   People who are referred by their health care provider for testing for another reason.\n\n**We do not recommend people get tested before visiting another household or attending a gathering just to make sure they're okay.** You could have already been exposed but may have been tested too early for it to show up on the test, or you could be exposed to COVID-19 after you are tested. Testing is not [prevention](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/about-coronavirus-disease-covid-19#prevention), and a negative test does not necessarily mean it is safe to gather with others.\n\n**We do not recommend people get tested frequently.** We do not recommend routine, repeated testing just for peace of mind. While testing supplies are currently in adequate supply, we need to use what we have wisely.\n\nThere is no cost to individuals for the COVID-19 test.\n\nThe number of Vermonters who were tested for COVID-19 is updated daily on the [Current Activity in Vermont data dashboard](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/current-activity-vermont).",
