            {
                "question": "What should people in long-term care facilities or group homes do?",
                "answerBody": "No visitors are allowed in nursing homes, assisted-living facilities and state therapeutic care residences. Medically necessary personnel and visitors for residents receiving end-of-life care are allowed.\n\nThe Health Department recommends that all health care personnel in long-term care facilities, correctional facilities, and other congregate settings where health care is provided wear face masks, regardless of the presence of COVID-19 in the facility.\n\nAny new admissions to nursing homes, assisted living residences, and residential care homes must complete the full 14-day quarantine period first.\n\n[Senior Centers and Adult Day Programs](https://dail.vermont.gov/sites/dail/files//documents/Adult_Day_and_Senior_Centers.pdf) have closed their programs in compliance with the Governor’s State of Emergency in Response to COVID-19.\n\nFind guidance for [long-term care and group living](https://www.healthvermont.gov/COVID19-longtermcare)\n[settings](https://www.healthvermont.gov/COVID19-longtermcare).",
                "date": "2020-06-15"
            },
            {
                "question": "What information is available for long-term care facilities and other facilities that serve older Vermonters (group homes, nursing homes, assisted living, and state therapeutic care residences)?",
                "answerBody": "Starting June 19, facilities may offer limited visitation outside with residents. Check with the facility first before planning a visit.\n\nMedically necessary personnel and visitors for residents receiving end-of-life care are allowed inside. Read the [executive order](https://governor.vermont.gov/sites/scott/files/documents/EO%2001-20%20Declaration%20of%20State%20of%20Emergency%20in%20Response%20to%20COVID-19%20and%20National%20Guard%20Call-Out.pdf).\n\nThe Health Department recommends that all health care personnel in long-term care facilities and other congregate settings where health care is provided wear face masks, regardless of the presence of COVID-19 in the facility.\n\nAny new admissions to nursing homes, assisted living residences, and residential care homes must complete the full 14-day quarantine period first.\n\nSenior Centers may reopen with guidance from the Health Department and the Department of Aging and Independent Living. Adult Day programs remain closed.\n\nThere is guidance ­on preventing the spread of COVID-19 for [managers and owners of senior living communities](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19-Prevention-Senior-Living-final.pdf), which includes making a plan, preparing common spaces and communicating with residents/staff, in addition to outlining the role of the Health Department.\n\nFind more guidance and information for [long-term care and group living settings](https:/www.healthvermont.gov/COVID19-longtermcare).",
                "date": "2020-06-17"
            },
            {
                "question": "What information is available for long-term care facilities and other facilities that serve older Vermonters (group homes, nursing homes, assisted living, and state therapeutic care residences)?",
                "answerBody": "Facilities may offer limited visitation outside with residents. Check with the facility first before planning a visit.\n\nLong-term care facilities can now ease some restrictions based on new phased guidance from the Department of Aging and Independent Living (DAIL). The guidance creates a framework for long-term care facilities to determine how to ease the restrictions on communal activities, non-essential personnel entering the building, trips outside the building and visitation.Check with the long-term care facility to find out what they are currently allowing.\n\nMedically necessary personnel and visitors for residents receiving end-of-life care are allowed inside. Read the [executive order](https://governor.vermont.gov/sites/scott/files/documents/EO%2001-20%20Declaration%20of%20State%20of%20Emergency%20in%20Response%20to%20COVID-19%20and%20National%20Guard%20Call-Out.pdf).\n\nThe Health Department recommends that all health care personnel in long-term care facilities and other congregate settings where health care is provided wear face masks, regardless of the presence of COVID-19 in the facility.\n\nAny new admissions to nursing homes, assisted living residences, and residential care homes must complete the full 14-day quarantine period first.\n\nSenior Centers may reopen with guidance from the Health Department and DAIL. Adult Day programs remain closed.\n\nThere is guidance ­on preventing the spread of COVID-19 for [managers and owners of senior living communities](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19-Prevention-Senior-Living-final.pdf), which includes making a plan, preparing common spaces and communicating with residents/staff, in addition to outlining the role of the Health Department.\n\nFind more guidance and information for [long-term care and group living settings](https:/www.healthvermont.gov/COVID19-longtermcare).",
                "date": "2020-07-21"
            },
            {
                "question": "What information is available for long-term care facilities and other facilities that serve older Vermonters (group homes, nursing homes, assisted living, and state therapeutic care residences)?",
                "answerBody": "Facilities may offer limited visitation outside with residents. Check with the facility first before planning a visit.\n\nLong-term care facilities can now ease some restrictions based on new phased guidance from the Department of Aging and Independent Living (DAIL). The guidance creates a framework for long-term care facilities to determine how to ease the restrictions on communal activities, non-essential personnel entering the building, trips outside the building and visitation. Check with the long-term care facility to find out what they are currently allowing.\n\nMedically necessary personnel and visitors for residents receiving end-of-life care are allowed inside. Read the [executive order](https://governor.vermont.gov/sites/scott/files/documents/EO%2001-20%20Declaration%20of%20State%20of%20Emergency%20in%20Response%20to%20COVID-19%20and%20National%20Guard%20Call-Out.pdf).\n\nThe Health Department recommends that all health care personnel in long-term care facilities and other congregate settings where health care is provided wear face masks, regardless of the presence of COVID-19 in the facility.\n\nResidents and staff of group living facilities and new admissions to nursing homes, assisted living residences, and residential care homes must complete the full 14-day quarantine period first.\n\nSenior Centers may reopen with guidance from the Health Department and DAIL. Adult Day programs remain closed.\n\nThere is guidance ­on preventing the spread of COVID-19 for [managers and owners of senior living communities](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19-Prevention-Senior-Living-final.pdf), which includes making a plan, preparing common spaces and communicating with residents/staff, in addition to outlining the role of the Health Department.\n\nFind more guidance and information for [long-term care and group living settings](https:/www.healthvermont.gov/COVID19-longtermcare).",
                "date": "2020-08-18"
            },
            {
                "question": "What information is available for long-term care facilities and other facilities that serve older Vermonters (group homes, nursing homes, assisted living, and state therapeutic care residences)?",
                "answerBody": "Facilities may offer visitation with residents. Check with the facility first before planning a visit.\n\nLong-term care facilities can ease some restrictions based on phased guidance from the Department of Aging and Independent Living (DAIL). The guidance creates a framework for long-term care facilities to determine how to ease the restrictions on communal activities, non-essential personnel entering the building, trips outside the building and visitation. Check with the long-term care facility to find out what they are currently allowing.\n\nMedically necessary personnel and visitors for residents receiving end-of-life care are allowed inside. Read the [executive order](https://governor.vermont.gov/sites/scott/files/documents/EO%2001-20%20Declaration%20of%20State%20of%20Emergency%20in%20Response%20to%20COVID-19%20and%20National%20Guard%20Call-Out.pdf).\n\nThe Health Department recommends that all health care personnel in long-term care facilities and other congregate care settings where health care is provided wear face masks, regardless of the presence of COVID-19 in the facility.\n\nResidents and staff of congregate care settings and new admissions to nursing homes, assisted living residences, and residential care homes must complete the full 14-day quarantine period. Testing out of quarantine after day 7 is not an option unless alternate guidance is provided by the Health Department.\n\nSenior centers and adult day centers may reopen with guidance from the Health Department and DAIL.\n\nThere is guidance ­on preventing the spread of COVID-19 for [managers and owners of senior living communities](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19-Prevention-Senior-Living-final.pdf), which includes making a plan, preparing common spaces and communicating with residents/staff, in addition to outlining the role of the Health Department.\n\nFind more guidance and information for [long-term care and group living settings](https:/www.healthvermont.gov/COVID19-longtermcare).",
                "date": "2020-10-14"
            },
