            {
                "question": "What do I do if I think I had close contact with someone who has COVID-19?",
                "answerBody": "If someone tests positive for COVID-19, they are contacted by the Health Department. They are asked questions about their activities within a certain timeframe – to help identify anyone they had close contact with. (Close contact means being closer than 6 feet apart for a long time while the person was infectious.) This is called contact tracing. \n\nIf the Health Department determines that you were a close contact of the person who tested positive, then the Health Department will call you to tell you [what you need to do](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19_What-to-do-if-you-are-a-close-contact-of-someone-with-COVID-19_final.pdf). \n\nIf the Health Department determines you are **not** a close contact, then you will not be called. You can continue to take the general precautions to slow the spread of the virus: wear a [face mask or covering](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19-VDH-mask-guidance.pdf), keep a 6-foot distance from others you do not live with, wash your hands often, and stay home if you are sick.",
                "date": "2020-07-29"
            },
            {
                "question": "What do I do if I think I had close contact with someone who has COVID-19?",
                "answerBody": "If someone tests positive for COVID-19, they are contacted by the Health Department. They are asked questions about their activities within a certain timeframe – to help identify anyone they had close contact with. (Close contact means being closer than 6 feet apart for a long time while the person was infectious. Other factors, such as the nature of the contact with the person, can influence who is determined a close contact.) This is called contact tracing.\n\nIf the Health Department determines that you were a close contact of the person who tested positive, then the Health Department will call you to tell you [what you need to do](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19_What-to-do-if-you-are-a-close-contact-of-someone-with-COVID-19_final.pdf).\n\nIf the Health Department determines you are **not** a close contact, then you will not be called. While contact tracers work to identify all close contacts, all might not be identified. If you think that you might be a close contact but didn't get a call from the Health Department, you may take precautions by quarantining for 14 days since the last day you were in contact with that person, and get tested on day 7 or after if you have not had any symptoms.\n\nIf you are not a close contact of a person who tested positive, you can continue to take the general precautions to slow the spread of the virus: wear a [face mask or covering](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19-VDH-mask-guidance.pdf), keep a 6-foot distance from others you do not live with, wash your hands often, and stay home if you are sick.",
