                "answerBody": "COVID-19 cases and deaths have been reported in all 50 states, and the situation is constantly changing. Travel increases your chances of getting and spreading COVID-19.\n\nAccording to the CDC, staying home is the best way to protect yourself and others from getting sick. Don’t travel if you are sick or if you have been around someone with COVID-19. Don’t travel with someone who is sick. Read about [travel during the COVID-19 pandemic](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/travel-during-covid19.html) if you are thinking of traveling away from your local community.\n\nVermonters may travel to [certain counties with low rates of active cases](https://accd.vermont.gov/covid-19/restart/cross-state-travel) (\"green\" counties). If you make your trip in a personal vehicle (including a rental vehicle or private plane), you do not need to quarantine upon return to Vermont. Learn about [what to do if the county “color” changes](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/COVID/faq/#4735) during your travel.\n\nIf you travel out of state to a location other than those counties with low rates of active cases, you must quarantine in Vermont for 14 days upon return. This includes day trips.\n\nYou have the [option to get a PCR test on day 7](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/COVID/faq/#4692) and end your quarantine with a negative test result.\n\nCheck the Health Department’s webpage for [what to do when you return to Vermont](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/traveling-vermont).",
