                "answerBody": "Social distancing means maintaining distance (approximately 6 feet or 2 meters) from others you do not live with. This includes when you're outside for a walk or exercise and when your at a grocery store, pharmacy.\n\nThe COVID-19 virus spreads easily from person to person. It travels through the air when a sick person coughs, sneezes or talks. One way to contain the spread of COVID-19 is to stop people from sharing it. Without a vaccine or treatment, we can help contain the virus by:\n\n* If you are sick, please stay home to protect others.\n\n* Staying home as much as possible, leaving only for essential reasons, such as personal safety, groceries or medicine, curbside pick-up of goods, meals or beverages, medical care, exercise, or care of others.\n\n* Limiting trips outside of the home for essential purposes by making sure you have enough groceries and other supplies for 14 days.\n\n* Continuing to go outside, take walks, go to the grocery store and pharmacies while practicing “social distancing” and proper hygiene. When you’re out walking or spending time in your backyard, remember that ticks are active this time of year. Stay safe by checking regularly for ticks and wearing EPA-registered tick repellents. See more information on how to [Be Tick Smart and prevent tick bites](https://www.healthvermont.gov/disease-control/tickborne-diseases/prevent-tick-bites-tickborne-diseases). \n\n* Wearing a [cloth face mask](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19-VDH-mask-guidance.pdf) whenever you leave home, especially at the grocery store, pharmacy, doctor’s office, hospital or other essential business or office, and when stopping to chat with people you encounter outside. \n\n* Limiting contact with family members and friends who are sick. This includes anyone who has symptoms of a cold, flu or contagious stomach illnesses. \n\n* Washing your hands (adults and children) any time you go inside, before you ea