                "question": "How can children socialize while still preventing the spread of COVID-19?",
                "answerBody": "Socializing is important for children’s development and wellbeing. There are ways children can socialize but still stay safe and keep from getting and spreading COVID-19.\n\n**We strongly recommend that any social gatherings you choose to have be with less than 10 people, and with a very limited number of trusted households**. Other ways to keep from getting and spreading COVID-19 are for everyone to follow these general prevention steps:\n\n*   Stay home if you are sick.\n*   Wash your hands often.\n*   Keep your social circle small.\n*   Stay at least 6 feet away from people you don't live with.\n*   Wear a mask (children over 2 who are able) when you’re outside and can’t keep 6 feet apart or anytime you’re inside with people you don’t live with.\n\nIf you choose to socialize with family, friends and neighbors, choose a very limited number of trusted households that are also taking these prevention steps in their day-to-day lives. \n\nWhenever possible, keep gatherings outdoors. Because of the nature of how the virus spreads and how it survives, [being indoors increases your risk](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/COVID/faq/#4746) of spreading or getting COVID-19. Sleepovers are considered high-risk and not recommended. Encourage children to spend time with friends in safer ways.\n\nThere will always be some risk of COVID-19 when we leave home, but it is possible to live your life and stay safer. Look for three things to help weigh the risk when making plans or going out:\n\n*   **6-Foot Spaces**: Can I easily keep 6 feet from others?\n*   **Masks on Faces**: Will people wear masks?\n*   **Uncrowded Places**: Is there enough space for people to spread out?\n\nImagine these things as layers protecting us from getting and spreading COVID-19. The more layers we have, the lower the risk. Find more [tips on preventing COVID-19](https://www.healthvermont.gov/staysafevt).\n\nChildren can also continue to take advantage of technology to play games or keep in touch with friends and family who you are not meeting up with in person. These changes will continue to be difficult, but we are all doing our part to slow down this pandemic.\n\n**Learn more:**\n\n*   [Resources for families with children](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/communities-and-workplaces#families)\n*   [Coping with family stress during COVID-19](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID19-Family-Coping-Fact-Sheet.pdf)\n*   [Face coverings for children](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID19-childfacecovering.pdf)\n*   [How to safely connect with friends and family](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/Safely_Connect_with_Friends_and_Family_FINAL.pdf)",
