                "question": "How do I wash or sanitize my hands to keep from getting sick?",
                "answerBody": "CDC recommends the following for hand hygiene: Household members should [clean hands often](https://www.cdc.gov/handwashing/when-how-handwashing.html), including immediately after removing gloves and after contact with someone who is ill, by washing hands with soap and water for 20 seconds. If soap and water are not available and hands are not visibly dirty, use an alcohol-based hand sanitizer that contains at least 60% alcohol. However, if hands are visibly dirty, always wash hands with soap and water.\n\n**Hand Sanitizer Recipe** (based on [recipe from the World Health Organization](https://www.who.int/gpsc/5may/Guide_to_Local_Production.pdf)):\n\n*   1 cup (250 mL) isopropyl\n     alcohol (91%)\n\n*   1 teaspoon (5 mL) glycerol\n     (or other moisturizer such as aloe vera gel, warm honey or olive oil)\n\n*   2 Tablespoons (33 mL) water\n\nAdd the ingredients in the order listed above to a clean container, mixing with a spoon. If using honey, stir until the honey is completely dissolved. Keep this mixture out of the reach of children. The final concentration of isopropyl alcohol in this mixture is 75%, so keep it away from flames.",
                "date": "2020-04-27"
            },
            {
                "question": "How do I wash or sanitize my hands to keep from getting sick?",
                "answerBody": "The CDC recommends [washing your hands often](https://www.cdc.gov/handwashing/when-how-handwashing.html) with soap and water for 20 seconds, including immediately after removing gloves and after contact with someone who is sick. If soap and water are not available, use an alcohol-based hand sanitizer that contains at least 60% alcohol. Always wash your hands with soap and water if they look dirty.\n\n**Hand Sanitizer Recipe** (based on a [recipe from the World Health Organization](https://www.who.int/gpsc/5may/Guide_to_Local_Production.pdf)):\n\n1 cup (250 mL) isopropyl\nalcohol (91%)\n\n1 teaspoon (5 mL) glycerol\n(or other moisturizer such as aloe vera gel, warm honey or olive oil)\n\n2 Tablespoons (33 mL) water\n\nAdd the ingredients in the order listed above to a clean container, mixing with a spoon. If using honey, stir until the honey is completely dissolved. Keep this mixture out of the reach of children. The final concentration of isopropyl alcohol in this mixture is 75%, so keep it away from flames.",
                "date": "2020-06-26"
            },
            {
                "question": "How do I wash or sanitize my hands to keep from getting sick?",
                "answerBody": "The CDC recommends [washing your hands often](https://www.cdc.gov/handwashing/when-how-handwashing.html) with soap and water for 20 seconds, including immediately after removing gloves and after contact with someone who is sick. If soap and water are not available, use an alcohol-based hand sanitizer that contains at least 60% alcohol. Always wash your hands with soap and water if they look dirty.",
                "date": "2020-09-03"
