            {
                "question": "How do I wash or sanitize my hands to keep from getting sick?",
                "answerBody": "The CDC recommends [washing your hands often](https://www.cdc.gov/handwashing/when-how-handwashing.html) with soap and water for 20 seconds. It’s especially important to wash your hands:\n\n*   Before touching your eyes, nose, or mouth because that’s how germs enter our bodies\n*   Before eating or preparing food\n*   After blowing your nose, coughing or sneezing\n*   After you have been in a public place and touched an item or surface that may be frequently touched by other people (such as door handles, tables, gas pumps, shopping carts, or electronic cashier registers/screens, etc.)\n*   After using the restroom\n*   After handling your mask\n*   After changing a diaper\n*   After caring for someone sick\n*   After touching animals or pets\n\nIf soap and water are not available, use an alcohol-based hand sanitizer that contains at least 60% alcohol. Cover all surfaces of your hands and rub them together until they feel dry. Always wash your hands with soap and water if they look dirty.",
                "date": "2020-10-19"
            }
