        "revisions": [
            {
                "question": "How can I stay connected while social distancing (being physically distant)?",
                "answerBody": "During this time of uncertainty, many Vermonters are feeling understandably angry, worried, and scared. Staying away from friends and family can make the feeling of isolation worse. We encourage all Vermonters to keep connections with family, friends, and your community in new ways. Use technology to communicate, enjoy the outdoors, take time to learn a new skill, follow up on long overdue projects, or volunteer to support those who may be in need. \n\n It is important to get outside for fresh air and exercise. Spend time outdoors as a family or consider individual outdoor activities like biking or hiking, as it’s easier to keep a good distance from each other. When you’re out walking or spending time in your backyard, remember that ticks are active this time of year. Stay safe by checking regularly for ticks and wearing EPA-registered tick repellents. For more information, visit [https://www.healthvermont.gov/disease-control/tickborne-diseases/prevent-tick-bites-tickborne-diseases](https://www.healthvermont.gov/disease-control/tickborne-diseases/prevent-tick-bites-tickborne-diseases).\n\nThis is a big transition in how we all live our daily lives – we’re all working together to adjust and change the way we express kindness and affection to others. Knowing this – all being in this together – goes into all the difficult decisions the State is making.",
                "date": "2020-04-27"
            },
            {
                "question": "How can I stay connected while social distancing (being physically distant)?",
                "answerBody": "During this time of uncertainty, many Vermonters are feeling understandably angry, worried, and scared. Staying away from friends and family can make the feeling of isolation worse. We encourage all Vermonters to keep connections with family, friends, and your community in new ways. Use technology to communicate, enjoy the outdoors, take time to learn a new skill, follow up on long overdue projects, or volunteer to support those who may be in need. \n\n It is important to get outside for fresh air and exercise. Spend time outdoors as a family or consider individual outdoor activities like biking or hiking, as it’s easier to keep a good distance from each other. When you’re out walking or spending time in your backyard, remember that ticks are active this time of year. Stay safe by checking regularly for ticks and wearing EPA-registered tick repellents. Learn how to how to [Be Tick Smart and prevent tick bites](https://www.healthvermont.gov/BeTickSmart).\n\nThis is a big transition in how we all live our daily lives – we’re all working together to adjust and change the way we express kindness and affection to others. Knowing this – all being in this together – goes into all the difficult decisions the State is making.\n\nLearn more about [coping with stress during the COVID-19 pandemic](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/coping-stress).",
                "date": "2020-04-28"
            },
            {
                "question": "How can I stay connected while social distancing (being physically distant)?",
                "answerBody": "Many of us are missing our friends and family. We want to know how we can safely connect and stay physically active, especially as the weather gets warmer.\n\nThe best way to lower our risk of getting or spreading COVID-19 is to stay home, but we have reached a point where we can take small steps to restart in-person connections. However, we all have a responsibility to do so thoughtfully. We are flattening the curve, but it won’t take much for cases and serious illness to quickly rocket back up if we are not careful.\n\nOlder adults (age 65 and over), and people with underlying medical conditions, like heart and lung disease or diabetes, are more likely to develop severe illness. They should continue to stay at home, and family and friends should do everything they can to help keep them safe.\n\nLearn how to [safely connect with friends and family](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/Safely_Connect_with_Friends_and_Family_FINAL.pdf). These recommended practices will help you weigh the risks and plan accordingly. ",
                "date": "2020-05-06"
            },
            {
                "question": "How can I stay connected while social distancing (being physically distant)?",
                "answerBody": "Many of us are missing our friends and family. We want to know how we can safely connect and stay physically active, especially as the weather gets warmer.\n\nThe best way to lower our risk of getting or spreading COVID-19 is to stay home, but we have reached a point where we can take small steps to restart in-person connections. However, we all have a responsibility to do so thoughtfully. We are flattening the curve, but it won’t take much for cases and serious illness to quickly rocket back up if we are not careful.\n\nThe risk for severe illness increases with age and is higher for older adults and people of any age with certain underlying medical conditions. Family and friends should do everything they can to help keep them safe.\n\nLearn how to [safely connect with friends and family](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/Safely_Connect_with_Friends_and_Family_FINAL.pdf). These recommended practices will help you weigh the risks and plan accordingly.",
