            {
                "question": "Does the Be Smart, Stay Safe Order mean I can be arrested or will need special papers if I leave my home?",
                "answerBody": "Enforcement of the Governor’s executive order extension — [Be Smart, Stay Safe](https://governor.vermont.gov/sites/scott/files/documents/ADDENDUM%2014%20TO%20EXECUTIVE%20ORDER%2001-20.pdf) — will be mainly be done through education and voluntary compliance.\n\n*   The Order does not close roads and does not establish roadblocks or checkpoints.\n*   Motor vehicle and pedestrian traffic will continue as Vermonters do outdoor activities that are allowed and travel to and from businesses and other entities that are open.\n*   There will not be motor vehicle stops or people detained for questioning about their travel, but law enforcement officers may be reminding people of the Order if they see groups gathering or businesses operating in violation of the Order.\n\nRead the latest updates to the [Be Smart, Stay Safe Executive Order](http://governor.vermont.gov/document-types/executive-orders)",
                "date": "2020-07-07"
            },
            {
                "question": "How is the Be Smart, Stay Safe Order enforced?",
                "answerBody": "Enforcement of the Governor’s executive order — [Be Smart, Stay Safe](https://governor.vermont.gov/document-types/executive-orders) — will be mainly done through education and voluntary compliance. \n\n*   Law enforcement officers may be reminding people of the Order if they see or are told about groups gathering or businesses operating in violation of the Order.\n*   The Order does not close roads, does not establish roadblocks or checkpoints, and does not require people to show their identification. \n*   People may be out and about. Motor vehicles with Vermont and out-of-state registrations are allowed to operate. Traffic is expected to increase as restrictions are eased. \n*   There will not be motor vehicle stops or people detained for questioning about their travel\n\nIf you have a concern about businesses, lodging establishments, short-term rental properties, nonprofits, other entities that are violating the Be Smart, Stay Safe Order or people who are not quarantining as required, call your local law enforcement agency.",
