                "answerBody": "Visitors from other states, and countries, are still being asked not to come to Vermont. If they do, they are required to quarantine for 14 days after arriving in Vermont and before engaging in any activities, like grocery shopping or going for walks.\n\nAnyone who leaves Vermont for more than one day for travel that is not “essential\" is required to quarantine at home for 14 days after arriving in Vermont and before engaging in any activities, like grocery shopping or going for walks.\n\nEssential travel is defined as travel necessary for personal safety, medical care, care of others, parental shared custody, for food, beverage or medicine, and to perform essential work or work for businesses that are currently allowed to operate. Read [Addendum 6](https://governor.vermont.gov/sites/scott/files/documents/ADDENDUM%206%20TO%20EXECUTIVE%20ORDER%2001-20.pdf) for more details.\n\nOvernight stays for necessary work-related travel by employees of essential businesses or other businesses currently allowed to operate and those who have completed the 14-day quarantine requirement are allowed in Vermont’s lodging, camping and short-term rental properties. However, employees must self-certify when they arrive that they are authorized to work in Vermont, have not been in contact with someone with COVID-19 in the past 24 hours, and have not experienced [COVID-19-like symptoms](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/about-coronavirus-disease-covid-19) in the past 24 hours. Find more details on [lodging and accommodations](https://accd.vermont.gov/content/stay-home-stay-safe-sector-specific-guidance#lodging-accommodations) from the Agency of Commerce and Community Development (ACCD).\n\nAnyone currently under quarantine who has had no symptoms during the first seven days of quarantine has the option to be tested at a pop-up testing site without a doctor’s referral. Registration is required. Find more details under [“I am under a