                "answerBody": "As of May 22, lodging facilities – hotels, motels, bed and breakfasts, inns, short-term rentals (for example, VRBO, Homeaway, Airbnb, etc.), and all public and private camping facilities, RV parks, seasonal resorts and marinas – may accept overnight reservations from Vermont residents, those who have met the quarantine requirement, and [essential workers](https://vem.vermont.gov/sites/demhs/files/Critical%20Service%20and%20Function%20GUidance.pdf).\n\nStaying home is still the best way to keep the virus from spreading. But if visitors do come to Vermont, they are required to quarantine in Vermont for 14 days before engaging in any activities, like grocery shopping or going for walks and must comply with all of the Governor’s [Be Smart, Stay Safe Order](https://governor.vermont.gov/covid19response). No lodging facility in Vermont can be used as a place to quarantine.\n\nAll reservations from out-of-state guests who cannot first meet the quarantine requirement must be canceled through June 15. The State may require similar reservations to be canceled after June 15.\n\nVisitors from counties in New York and New England with low numbers of active infections do not need to quarantine when they arrive in Vermont. Read the [travel guidance](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID19-Vermont-Visitors-and-Returning-Travelers.pdf), and check the [map of approved counties](https://accd.vermont.gov/covid-19/restart/cross-state-travel), which is updated weekly.\n\nAll guests must complete a [health questionnaire](https://accd.vermont.gov/content/pre-screening-health-survey-employees-and-visitors-entering-state-vermont-facilities) upon check-in and must provide a Vermont driver’s license or [signed document](https://accd.vermont.gov/content/be-smart-stay-safe-certificate-of-compliance) certifying that they met the quarantine and travel requirements. Out-of-state guests must register with [Sara Alert](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/EpiInfoWebSurvey/Home/9c2e5941-1ba7-4ab4-84be-558ba7684f5d) – a free, automated and secure reminder system to check for [common symptoms of COVID-19](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/about-coronavirus-disease-covid-19) – for daily reminders from the Vermont Department of Health.\n\nAnyone currently under quarantine who has had no symptoms during the first seven days of quarantine has the option to be tested at a pop-up testing site without a doctor’s referral. Registration for testing is required. Find more details under [“I am under a 14-day quarantine. Can I have the option to be tested and end my quarantine period?”](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/COVID/faq/#4692) on this page.\n\nFind more details and up-to-date information on [lodging, campgrounds and other accommodations](https://accd.vermont.gov/news/update-new-work-safe-additions-be-smart-stay-safe-order#lodging-campgrounds-and-other-accommodations) from the Agency of Commerce and Community and Development (ACCD).\n\nIf an individual has concerns about lodging facilities that are violating the Be Smart, Stay Safe Order, the Department of Public Safety has created an online [non-compliance complaint form](http://forms.office.com/Pages/ResponsePage.aspx?id=O5O0IK26PEOcAnDtzHVZxp8VoIcMV9NNu0QyG_vdGAVUN1pLSTdOMERRR1dXOVpZMDBZUEtNVlhXMi4u) to gather more information.",
