                "question": "Can I volunteer to help with the State’s response to COVID-19?",
                "answerBody": "Yes, people with medical and health care skills and those with other needed skills can sign up for volunteer assistance to support the state’s response to COVID-19.\n\nPeople with medical or other health care backgrounds are needed to support the health care providers responding to the COVID-19 pandemic. Vermont’s Medical Reserve Corp units are community-based groups of volunteers who supplement local emergency and public health resources with their existing skills. \n\nSign up with the [Vermont Medical Reserve Corps](https://www.vermont.gov/volunteer) if you:\n\n* Are a licensed and certified health care professional\n\n* Have health, mental health, or other types of clinical or professional experience \n\n* Have health care administrative experience, such as with medical data entry or language translators\n\n* Have worked with displaced individuals, such as homeless shelter programs\n\nVermont has eased licensing requirements for the purposes of aiding this emergency response. Physicians, physician assistants and podiatrists can learn more on the [Board of Medical Practice website](https://www.healthvermont.gov/health-professionals-systems/board-medical-practice/COVID19). Other medical professionals, including nurses and osteopathic physicians, can learn more on the [Office of Professional Regulation's website](https://sos.vermont.gov/opr/about-opr/covid-19-response/).\n\n**Other individuals who have needed skills** (for example, drivers, food service, construction, IT, security, skilled trades, etc.), can sign up at [vermont.gov/volunteer](https://www.vermont.gov/volunteer) and indicate their expertise and availability.\n\nVermonters can also contribute to blood banks, food banks, and other emergency supply efforts. The American Red Cross of Northern New England faces a severe blood shortage and many local food banks and other community organizations are in need of support and donations of supplies. \n\n**Give blood**: Learn how to safely [donate blood with the American Red Cross](https://www.redcross.org/local/new-hampshire-vermont.html). \n\nSupport your [local Foodbank by donating online](https://www.vtfoodbank.org/) or you can text GIVEHEALTH to 85511. The [Vermont Foodbank can help](https://www.vtfoodbank.org/gethelp) if you need it.\n\nYou can also help your neighbors – older adults (65 years and older) and people of any age who have underlying medical conditions should stay home as much as possible. Go shopping for a neighbor or someone else in need, keep an older neighbor company by phone or at a safe distance. When volunteering please follow the [guidelines on being a good neighbor](https://vem.vermont.gov/neighborly).",
