                "answerBody": "Under the Governor’s executive order extension — [Be Smart, Stay Safe](https://governor.vermont.gov/sites/scott/files/documents/ADDENDUM%2014%20TO%20EXECUTIVE%20ORDER%2001-20.pdf) — Vermonters are encouraged to limit their exposure to the COVID-19 virus outside their homes as much as possible.\n\nVermonters should travel only as needed:\n\n*   For personal safety, medical care and care of others\n*   For work, although all workers should continue to work remotely whenever possible\n*   For shopping and services available at all businesses and non-profit and government entities determined to be critical and those which have been authorized to resume operations\n*   To get fresh air and exercise by taking advantage of outdoor recreation and outdoor fitness activities that require low or no direct physical contact\n*   For in-state stays at available lodging, campground and marina facilities\n\nVermonters should follow health and safety precautions to help keep the virus from spreading by:\n\n*   Staying home and away from others if you are sick with COVID-19, have recently been exposed to someone who has COVID-19, or just don’t feel well.\n*   Keeping a physical distance of at least 6 feet away from others (except for those you live with).\n*   Washing or sanitizing your hands often.\n*   Wearing a [face mask or covering](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19-VDH-mask-guidance.pdf) in public settings when a physical distance of at least 6 feet is difficult to maintain (for example, at a grocery store or on a crowded sidewalk or bike path).\n*   Coughing and sneezing into your elbow (even when wearing a face covering).\n*   Limiting travel to within Vermont, or to [places that have been identified as low risk](https://accd.vermont.gov/covid-19/restart/cross-state-travel), as much as possible and limiting non-essential stops when you do travel.\n\nThe risk for severe illness increases with age and is higher for older adults and people of any age with certain underlying medical conditions. They should consider [taking additional steps to limit their risk](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/COVID/faq/#4559).\n\nLearn how to [safely connect with friends and family](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/Safely_Connect_with_Friends_and_Family_FINAL.pdf). These recommended practices will help you weigh the risk and plan accordingly.\n\nRead the latest updates to the [Be Smart, Stay Safe Order](http://governor.vermont.gov/document-types/executive-orders).\n\nThe Agency of Commerce and Community Development has [resources for individuals](https://accd.vermont.gov/covid-19/individuals) and [sector-specific guidance](https://accd.vermont.gov/content/stay-home-stay-safe-sector-specific-guidance) for details on which businesses are open.",
