            {
                "question": "Does the Be Smart, Stay Safe Order ban travel to neighboring states for work or court-ordered parental visitation?",
                "answerBody": "No. If you work in a neighboring state, or if you need to drop off or pick up children from court-ordered parental visits, for example, that is considered essential travel, and you do not need to quarantine.\n\nHowever, if you come in close contact with someone sick with COVID-19, you should self-quarantine for 14 days, no matter where the contact occurred.\n\nLearn more about [what to do if you’re a close contact of someone with COVID-19](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19_What-to-do-if-you-are-a-close-contact-of-someone-with-COVID-19_final.pdf).\n\nAnyone currently under quarantine who has had no symptoms during the first seven days of quarantine has the option to be tested. Find out how under [“I am under a 14-day quarantine. Can I have the option to be tested and end my quarantine period?”](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/COVID/faq/#4692) on this page.\n\nFind out more about [traveling to Vermont](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/traveling-vermont).",
