            {
                "question": "Do I need to quarantine if I work in a neighboring state or have parental shared custody?",
                "answerBody": "No. If you live near a border and regularly travel to and from a neighboring state, you may make day trips to that state for work, health care, and other essential needs like groceries or visitation for parental shared custody, without quarantining.\n\nHowever, if you come in close contact with someone sick with COVID-19, you should self-quarantine for 14 days, no matter where the contact occurred. Learn more about [what to do if you’re a close contact of someone with COVID-19](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19_What-to-do-if-you-are-a-close-contact-of-someone-with-COVID-19_final.pdf).\n\nIf you travel out of state for another reason and to a location that is **not** in an [approved county with low rates of active cases](https://accd.vermont.gov/covid-19/restart/cross-state-travel), you must quarantine for 14 days in Vermont upon return. This includes day trips. Find up-to-date information about [travel and COVID-19](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/traveling-vermont).\n\nAnyone currently under quarantine who has had no symptoms during the first seven days of quarantine has the option to be tested with a PCR test. Find out how under [“I am under a 14-day quarantine. Can I have the option to be tested and end my quarantine period?”](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/COVID/faq/#4692) on this page.",
                "date": "2020-07-24"
            },
            {
                "question": "Do I need to quarantine if I'm traveling for an essential purpose (like work in a neighboring state or parental shared custody)?",
                "answerBody": "If you are traveling for essential purposes, you do not need to quarantine. Essential travel includes travel for personal safety, medical care, care of others, parental shared custody, for food, beverage or medicine, or for work.\n\nIf you live near a border and regularly travel to and from a neighboring state, you may make day trips to that state for work, health care, and other essential needs like groceries or visitation for parental shared custody, without quarantining.\n\nHowever, if you come in close contact with someone sick with COVID-19, you should self-quarantine for 14 days, no matter where the contact occurred. Learn more about [what to do if you’re a close contact of someone with COVID-19](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19_What-to-do-if-you-are-a-close-contact-of-someone-with-COVID-19_final.pdf).\n\nIf you travel out of state for leisure and to a location that is **not** in an [approved county with low rates of active cases](https://accd.vermont.gov/covid-19/restart/cross-state-travel), you must quarantine for 14 days in Vermont upon return. This includes day trips. Find up-to-date information about [travel and COVID-19](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/traveling-vermont).\n\nAnyone currently under quarantine who has had no symptoms during the first seven days of quarantine has the option to be tested with a PCR test. Find out how under [“I am under a 14-day quarantine. Can I have the option to be tested and end my quarantine period?”](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/COVID/faq/#4692) on this page.\n\nFind more [travel and quarantine information](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/traveling-vermont) and answers to [frequently asked questions about travel](https://accd.vermont.gov/covid-19/restart/cross-state-travel/faqs).",
