                "answerBody": "We encourage Vermonters to go outside and enjoy the fresh air. Exercise, outdoor activities, and taking in Vermont’s natural beauty is important for our mind and bodies. As the weather warms up, be sure to follow these [summer safety tips](https://www.healthvermont.gov/summer-safety-tips).\n\nBusinesses, non-profit and government entities that support or offer outdoor recreation and outdoor fitness activities with low or no direct physical contact are open under certain health and safety requirements. These include, but are not limited to, state and municipal parks, recreation associations, pools, beaches, trail networks, golf courses, big game check stations and guided expeditions.\n\nFind up-to-date [information on outdoor recreation](https://accd.vermont.gov/news/update-new-work-safe-additions-be-smart-stay-safe-order#outdoor-recreation-and-fitness) and [campgrounds](https://accd.vermont.gov/news/update-new-work-safe-additions-be-smart-stay-safe-order#lodging-campgrounds-and-other-accommodations) from the Agency of Commerce and Community Development (ACCD).\n\nSports with no contact or low contact and team sports are allowed. Practices and scrimmages can resume as long as there are 25 or fewer participants. Wearing cloth face masks or coverings and keeping a 6-foot distance from others is recommended whenever possible. Find up-to-date information on [sports and organized sports](https://accd.vermont.gov/news/update-new-work-safe-additions-stay-home-stay-safe-order#sports-and-organized-sports) from the ACCD.\n\nWe can safely continue to enjoy outdoor activities with these measures:\n\n*   **Stay close to home**. Find local outdoor recreation areas and consider day trips that are close to home. Only drive with members of your household.\n*   **Take health and safety precautions**. Keep the virus from spreading by staying at least 6 feet apart from other people outside of your household, washing or sanitizing your hands, and staying home when you are sick.\n*   **Bring a cloth face mask or covering with you**. Put a [cloth face mask or covering](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19-VDH-mask-guidance.pdf) on if you encounter other people and stop to chat or if you are on a crowded trail or bike path.\n*   **Be cautious and choose low-risk activities to avoid injury**. This will help lower the burden on our hospitals and health care system.\n*   **Respect signs for closed areas, trails and land**. Check [Trail Finder](http://www.trailfinder.info/) to see if your trail is currently open before you visit. Call ahead or check websites for information on outdoor recreation facilities before you head out.\n*   **Choose low- or no-contact sports**: For example, biking, hiking, horseback riding, tennis, boating and golfing. Outdoor basketball courts may be open to shoot hoops, but signage should be posted prohibiting contact games. Do not share sports equipment with people outside of your household.\n*   **Check for ticks and wear an EPA-registered tick repellent**. When you’re out walking or spending time in your backyard, remember that ticks are active this time of year. Find out how to [Be Tick Smart prevent tick bites](https://www.healthvermont.gov/BeTickSmart).\n\nFind out more about outdoor recreation and COVID-19 from the [Vermont Department of Forests, Parks and Recreation](https://fpr.vermont.gov/recreation/outdoor-recreation-and-covid-19) and the [Vermont Fish and Wildlife Department](https://vtfishandwildlife.com/outdoor-recreation-and-covid-19).\n\nLearn how to [safely connect with friends and family](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/Safely_Connect_with_Friends_and_Family_FINAL.pdf).",
