            {
                "question": "When will COVID-19 infections peak? When will the “Stay Home, Stay Safe” Order end?",
                "answerBody": " \n\nMost recent modeling data suggests Vermont has likely reached its peak in the number of new cases of COVID-19 and hospital capacity. We are also close to reaching the peak of the number people who are currently infected with COVID-19 in Vermont. However, it’s important to remember there are still many who currently infected and therefore, are contagious and could spread it to others.\n\nVermont is looking at four key measures to inform steps to reopen:\n\n1. Ongoing reduction in cases for at least 14 days\n\n2. Health care system that is safely able to treat all patients without exceeding its capacity or using crisis standards of care\n\n3. Ability to test all people with symptoms\n\n4. Widespread active monitoring of people who have tested positive for COVID-19 and tracing their close contacts\n\nAt this time, Vermont has seen a reduction in cases for at least 14 days. This is hopeful news. To continue on this path, it is critical that Vermonters continue making their day-to-day sacrifices to help save lives. Social distancing (staying at least 6 feet from each other) and wearing face masks are here to stay for a while, even as we being to reopen, until we have effective antiviral medicines or a vaccine.\n\nRead the latest [Vermont COVID-19 modeling projections](http://dfr.vermont.gov/about-us/covid-19/modeling).",
                "date": "2020-04-27"
