                "question": "What should I do if I have a dental emergency?",
                "answerBody": "There are some cases where you may need to see a dentist. Some in-person treatment options may be limited because some dental treatments produce aerosol, which raises the risk of spreading COVID-19. And in some cases, complete care may not be safe to provide during the pandemic.\n\nIf you are experiencing one of the following symptoms or situations, then you should contact your regular dentist: \n * Heavy bleeding that won’t stop \n * Painful swelling in or around your mouth \n * Pain in a tooth, teeth or jawbone \n * Gum infection with pain or swelling \n * Treatment after surgery (dressing change, stitch removal) \n * Broken or knocked out tooth \n * Denture adjustment for people receiving radiation or other treatment for cancer \n * Wire of braces poking your cheek or gums \n * Biopsy of abnormal tissue\n\nYou can contact your regular dentist by: \n * Phone – calling or texting \n * Video chats through FaceTime, Skype, Facebook Messenger or Google Hangouts\n\nIf you don’t have a regular dentist, call 211, and they can assist you in finding one.\n\nThe dentist will ask you if you have a fever (take a current temperature reading), dry cough, or trouble breathing. They will be able to give you advice to alleviate pain, swelling or other urgent issue.\n\nFor more information on what is a dental emergency, please check the [American Dental Association’s patient guide](https://www.mouthhealthy.org/en/dental-care-concerns/covid-19).",
                "date": "2020-04-27"
            },
