                "answerBody": "There are some cases where you may need to see a dentist. Some in-person treatment options may be limited because some dental treatments produce aerosol, which raises the risk of spreading COVID-19.\n\nStarting May 22, dentists can perform procedures with a low risk of generating aerosol. Beginning June 1, if Vermont continues to be able to safely reopen, dentists will be able to perform some procedures that have a higher risk of generating aerosol.\n\nContact your dentist to find out if you can be seen. If you don’t have a regular dentist and need help finding one, call 211.\n\nDo not delay care if you have:\n\n*   Heavy bleeding that won’t stop\n*   Painful swelling in or around your mouth\n*   Pain in a tooth, teeth or jawbone\n*   Gum infection with pain or swelling\n*   Treatment after surgery (dressing change, stitch removal)\n*   Broken or knocked out tooth\n*   Denture adjustment for people receiving radiation or other treatment for cancer\n*   Wire of braces poking your cheek or gums\n*   Biopsy of abnormal tissue\n\nThe dental community is confident it has the necessary knowledge, skills, office processes and equipment, testing protocols, and personal protective equipment (PPE) to safely provide care.",
