                "question": "Can property management and landscaping businesses still operate under the Stay Home, Stay Safe Order?",
                "answerBody": "Governor Phil Scott has amended the Stay Home, Stay Safe Executive Order. There is now new guidance for the reopening of certain businesses in strict accordance with mandatory health and safety requirements, including outdoor businesses. See up-to-date [sector-specific guidance from the Agency of Commerce and Community Development (ACCD)](http://accd.vermont.gov/content/stay-home-stay-safe-sector-specific-guidance). Guidance includes requiring employees to wear non-medical cloth face coverings (bandanna, scarf, or non-medical mask, etc.) over their nose and mouth when in the presence of others.\n\nThe governor’s Stay Home, Stay Safe Order says that “other building and property services for the safety, sanitation and operations of residences or other businesses” are considered critical. This means that property management and landscaping businesses may do limited in-person operations under the governor’s Stay Home, Stay Safe Order. According to the ACCD, these include building services such as janitorial services, security services, pest control and maintenance and repair operations that are essential to protecting property.\n\nAll businesses in operation must complete and document [mandatory health and safety training](https://labor.vermont.gov/VOSHA) developed by the Vermont Occupational Safety and Health Administration (VOSHA) by May 4, 2020.\n\nFind more [health resources for businesses](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/communities-and-workplaces) and read the [Health &amp; Safety Tips for Essential Businesses](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID19-Essential-Workers-Health-Safety-Tips.pdf).",
