            {
                "question": "Who is getting tested for COVID-19 in Vermont?",
                "answerBody": "Currently, health care providers can arrange testing for any child or adult who is showing symptoms of COVID-19, including those with mild symptoms. All residents and staff in group living settings, where there has been a single positive test, can also be tested. This includes nursing homes, assisted living facilities, prisons, and certain high-density residential buildings.\n\nWe are now working to ramp up our testing capabilities to conduct 1,000 tests a day – or 7,000 tests a week. That is about three times the average number of tests conducted over the last several weeks. We know that with increased testing we are likely to see a rise in positive cases, and we are prepared to handle such a scenario. A new Testing and Tracing Task Force has been created to guide and oversee this process.\n\nAs of April 29, we will now be able to expand testing for:\n\n* **Long-term care facilities and other group living settings**: If there is a person who has tested positive with COVID-19, they can be retested 3, 7, 10 and 14 days later. This is to help prevent community-wide outbreaks. For all sites, regardless of whether a person has tested positive, we will provide testing at intake, discharge, and for certain residents who require regular care outside of the facility.\n\n* **Health care personnel**: Testing will now be available for those who may have been exposed to patients who have tested positive for COVID-19, but who do not have symptoms themselves. Testing will also be offered to health care personnel who may be needed to aid their Restart Vermont efforts.\n\n* **Correctional facilities**: Now all corrections staff and inmates can be tested in the correctional facility, regardless if there has been a person who has tested positive for COVID-19.\n\nDuring the next phase, we will focus on expanded testing for health care and home health workers who have had direct contact with someone who tested positive for COVID-19. We will also consider 