                "answerBody": "Vermonters can get together with friends and family. There are no group size limits to social gatherings and parties that are not held at [event venues](https://accd.vermont.gov/news/update-new-work-safe-additions-stay-home-stay-safe-order#event-venues). However, municipalities may choose to limit the size of gatherings, so check with your local office.\n\nWe recommend keeping groups small whenever possible to limit any possible exposure to the virus, and for everyone to follow these general prevention steps:\n\n*   Stay home if you are sick.\n*   Wash your hands often.\n*   Keep your social circle small.\n*   Stay at least 6 feet away from people you don't live with.\n*   Wear a mask when you’re outside and can’t keep 6 feet apart or anytime you’re inside with people you don’t live with.\n\nChoose other trusted households that are also taking these prevention steps in their day-to-day lives.\n\nWhenever possible, keep gatherings outdoors. Because of the nature of how the virus spreads and how it survives, [being indoors increases your risk](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/COVID/faq/#4746) of spreading or getting COVID-19.\n\nThere will always be some risk of COVID-19 when we leave home, but it is possible to live your life and stay safer. Look for three things to help weigh the risk when making plans or going out:\n\n*   **6-Foot Spaces**: Can I easily keep 6 feet from others?\n*   **Masks on Faces**: Will people wear masks?\n*   **Uncrowded Places**: Is there enough space for people to spread out?\n\nImagine these things as layers protecting us from getting and spreading COVID-19. The more layers we have, the lower the risk. Find more [tips on preventing COVID-19](https://www.healthvermont.gov/staysafevt).\n\nAlso, consider keeping a contact journal – a list of other people who you have been in close contact with each day. If you do get sick, this would make it easier to get in touch with those people and so they can take proper precautions to prevent further spread of the virus.\n\nThe risk for severe illness increases with age and is higher for older adults and people of any age with certain underlying medical conditions. They should consider [taking additional steps to limit their risk](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/COVID/faq/#4559), stay close to home, and family and friends should do everything they can to help keep them safe.\n\n**Learn more**:\n\n*   [How to safely connect with friends and family](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/Safely_Connect_with_Friends_and_Family_FINAL.pdf)\n*   [Hosting gatherings or cook-outs](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/daily-life-coping/personal-social-activities.html#gatherings) from the CDC\n*   [Attending an event or gathering](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/daily-life-coping/personal-social-activities.html#event) from the CDC\n*   [Holiday celebrations](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/daily-life-coping/holidays.html) from the CDC",
