                "question": "I am under a 14-day quarantine. Can I have the option to be tested and end my quarantine period?",
                "answerBody": "Anyone currently under quarantine who has had no symptoms during the first seven days of quarantine has the option to be tested at a [pop-up testing site](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/Pop-up-Testing-FAQs.pdf) without a doctor’s referral. Registration for testing is required.\n\nBased on data in the medical literature, the vast majority of people who are going to develop symptoms will do so by Day 7. For this reason, we offer what we consider to be a low-risk option for people to be tested at Day 7 or after in their quarantine and, if the test is negative, to end quarantine. This is simply an option, and it may not be practical or desirable for everyone.\n\nThe testing option is for:\n\n*   people returning to Vermont (for example, those who spend winter outside of Vermont, second homeowners and college students) who are required to quarantine when they arrive\n*   visitors coming into Vermont who are required to quarantine when they arrive\n*   close contacts of people who have tested positive* (see more details below)\n\nFor anyone coming into Vermont, Day 1 is the day after you arrive in Vermont.\n\nNew admissions to nursing homes, assisted living residences, and residential care homes must complete the full 14-day quarantine.\n\n**You can end your quarantine period before 14 days only if**:\n\n*   You have not had [symptoms](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/about-coronavirus-disease-covid-19) during your quarantine period;\n*   You are tested on Day 7 or later;\n*   You remain in quarantine until the result comes back; AND\n*   You receive a negative test result and are still not having symptoms.\n\nHowever, if you end your quarantine period before 14 days, you must continue to monitor yourself for symptoms for the full 14 days. If you develop symptoms at any point during your quarantine, contact your health care provider and the Health Department right away. If you do not have a health care provider, call 2-1-1.\n\nYou can [sign up to receive daily symptom check reminders](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/EpiInfoWebSurvey/Home/9c2e5941-1ba7-4ab4-84be-558ba7684f5d) with Sara Alert, a free, automated and secure reminder system to check for common COVID-19 symptoms. Sara Alert is not a contact tracing system. It is not GPS based, so it does not monitor your movements. If you report any symptoms of COVID-19 through Sara Alert, a member of the Health Department’s team will contact you with guidance and next steps.\n\n**\\*** For **close contacts** of people who have tested positive:\n\n*   **If you are NOT able to completely physically separate yourself** from the person who tested positive – for example, you live in the same home – Day 1 of your quarantine is the day after they have ended their self-isolation.\n*   **If you are able to completely physically separate** from the person who tested positive – for example you do not live in the same home – Day 1 of your quarantine is the day after the last time you were in close contact with them.\n*   In addition to getting tested at pop-up testing sites, you can also get tested through your health care provider, Federally Qualified Health Centers, commercial testing sites, and other testing sites as they come on board.",
