                "answerBody": "Anyone currently under quarantine who has had no symptoms during the first seven days of quarantine has the option to be tested. The test must be a PCR test. Talk to your health care provider to find out where to get tested.\n\nIf you do not have a health care provider, call 2-1-1 to be connected to care, or contact the nearest [federally qualified health center](https://bistatepca.org/community-resources/vt-health-centers) or one of [Vermont’s free & referral clinics](https://vtfreeclinics.org/).\n\nFor travelers who are [completing quarantine in their home state](https://www.healthvermont.gov/covid-19/travel-quarantine/visitors-vermont), your home state may offer testing for people without symptoms. Continue to quarantine until you travel to Vermont.\n\n**You can end your quarantine period before 14 days only if**:\n\n*   You have not had [symptoms](https://www.healthvermont.gov/covid-19/symptoms-sickness/symptoms) during your quarantine period;\n*   You are tested on day 7 or later;\n*   You remain in quarantine until the result comes back; AND\n*   You receive a negative test result and are still not having symptoms.\n*   You continue to monitor yourself for symptoms for the full 14 days.\n\nFor anyone coming into Vermont, day 1 is the day after you arrive in Vermont.\n\nIf you develop symptoms at any point during your quarantine, contact your health care provider and the Health Department right away. [Sign up to receive daily symptom check reminders](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/EpiInfoWebSurvey/Home/9c2e5941-1ba7-4ab4-84be-558ba7684f5d).\n\nYou will be contacted if you are you are a [close contact](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/COVID/faq/#4575) of someone who tested positive for COVID-19. The notification could come from the Health Department, your employer, school, or health care provider, for example. Learn more about [how contact tracing works](https://www.healthvermont.gov/covid-19/symptoms-sickness/close-contacts-contact-tracing) and see [scenarios from the CDC to determine when you can end quarantine](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/if-you-are-sick/quarantine.html) and be around others.\n\nStudies have found most people will develop symptoms by day 7. This is why there is the option for people to be tested on day 7 or after in their quarantine and, if the test is negative, to end quarantine.\n\nResidents and staff of group living facilities (for example long-term care facilities or corrections facilities) and new admissions to nursing homes, assisted living residences, and residential care homes **must complete the full 14-day quarantine**.",
                "date": "2020-11-13"
            }
