            {
                "question": "Is it safe to send my children back to school or child care?",
                "answerBody": "Yes, based on current data and levels of the COVID-19 virus in Vermont, it is safe – and important – for children to go to school or child care for in-person learning. On July 27, the Vermont Chapter of the American Academy of Pediatrics asked schools to prioritize in-person attendance for preschool to grade 5, and for students with special needs.\n\nWe know much more about the virus now than we did in March when schools closed for the spring. The Health Department can track data in real time and respond to cases quickly with our contact tracing teams. We also have robust testing and contact tracing system in Vermont that will support schools in containing the virus if there is a case.\n\nChildren need structure, relationships with their peers, teachers, and other adults for their academic, social, and emotional development. Although remote learning is an important tool during the pandemic, it can lead to even greater gaps in equity. Public health and education experts considered all these factors when writing Vermont’s guidance to reopen schools, which focuses on the safety of teachers, staff, and students.\n\nWe are seeing more cases of COVID-19 in children nationwide and in Vermont, but that is not surprising as states have reopened, and more testing has become available.\n\nWe recognize there may be cases in schools as they reopen. This is why Vermont’s reopening guidance outlines ways to keep the virus out of schools and prevent it from spreading through physical distancing, face masks or coverings, hand hygiene, and contact tracing.",
