                "question": "Is it safe to travel for the holidays?",
                "answerBody": "As Vermont sees a significant surge of new COVID-19 cases across the state, Vermonters are prohibited from gathering with people from other households beginning November 14, 2020. This includes both inside and outside social gatherings, and in public and private spaces. People who live alone may gather with members of their immediate family living in a different household. Read Governor Scott’s [Executive Order](https://governor.vermont.gov/sites/scott/files/documents/ADDENDUM%208%20TO%20AMENDED%20AND%20RESTATED%20EXECUTIVE%20ORDER%2001-20.pdf).\n\nAdditionally, the Health Department strongly advises against non-essential travel, even within Vermont. **Any non-essential travel to and from Vermont requires **[**quarantine**](https://www.healthvermont.gov/covid-19/travel-quarantine/vermonters-traveling-out-state). \n\nIf you do travel, you will be required to quarantine for 14 days when you return to Vermont. If you have not had [symptoms of COVID-19](https://www.healthvermont.gov/covid-19/symptoms-sickness/symptoms), you have the [option to get a PCR test on day 7](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/COVID/faq/#4692) and end your quarantine with a negative test result.\n\nIf people do visit you, they will need to quarantine at the place they are staying for 14 days. (They have the [option to get a PCR test on day 7](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/COVID/faq/#4692) and end their quarantine with a negative test result if they don’t have symptoms of COVID-19). If you are hosting them, you don’t also need to quarantine, but you’ll need to make sure there is a [separate space](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/COVID/faq/#4704https://apps.health.vermont.gov/COVID/faq/) for the people in quarantine.\n\nRemember, the virus can spread easily among family and friends — because they are the ones we are often in close contact with — when they don’t know they have it. Like other aspects of our lives, this holiday season will look different and we need to do everything we can to keep each other safe.\n\nBe sure to talk to the people who are visiting you about your comfort level with [COVID-19 prevention steps](https://www.healthvermont.gov/covid-19/protect-yourself-others/prevent-covid-19). \n\nCelebrating holidays within your own household or sharing a meal virtually will not be the same as we’re used to, but we need to keep our guard up and continue to do all we can to keep from getting or spreading COVID-19.\n\n**Find more tips from the CDC:**\n\n*   [Holiday celebrations and small gatherings](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/daily-life-coping/holidays.html)\n*   [Hosting gatherings or cook-outs](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/daily-life-coping/personal-social-activities.html#gatherings)\n*   [Attending an event or gathering](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/daily-life-coping/personal-social-activities.html#event)\n*   [Celebrating Thanksgiving](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/daily-life-coping/holidays/thanksgiving.html)",
