                "question": "What do I do if I’m diagnosed with COVID-19?",
                "answerBody": "Most people with mild illness can recover at home. While there is no specific treatment for COVID-19, you should get plenty of rest, drink plenty of fluids, and take fever-reducing medication if needed.\n\nIf you or a family member are sick, follow these steps to care for yourself and to help protect other people in your home and your community:\n\n**Isolate at home**\n\n*   **Stay home,** except to get medical care. Call ahead before visiting your health care provider. Anyone who does not have a health care provider can call 2-1-1 to be connected to care or contact the nearest [federally qualified health center(link is external)](https://bistatepca.org/community-resources/vt-health-centers) or one of [Vermont's free & referral clinics](https://vtfreeclinics.org/).\n*   **Separate yourself** from other people and pets**.**\n*   **Monitor your symptoms.**\n*   **Wear a** [face mask or covering](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19-VDH-mask-guidance.pdf) when you're around people and pets.\n*   **Cover your coughs and sneezes** with your sleeve or a tissue, then throw the tissue in the trash.\n*   **Wash your hands often.** Use an alcohol-based sanitizer if soap and water aren't available.\n*   **Avoid sharing** personal household items**.**\n*   **Clean all high-touch surfaces** in your home daily.\n*   **Get support from others.** Stay in touch with family and friends by phone, email or online platform.\n\nWe strongly encourage you to enroll in [Sara Alert](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/EpiInfoWebSurvey/Home/9c2e5941-1ba7-4ab4-84be-558ba7684f5d), a secure monitoring and reporting text-based system to help you monitor symptoms.\n\nSomeone from the Health Department will contact you to ask for your help with [contact tracing](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/about-coronavirus-disease-covid-19#contacttracing). Contact tracing is used to provide education, support and guidance to people who are diagnosed with an infectious disease. It’s also used to identify people who have been in close contact with them, so they can take steps to stop the disease from spreading to others.\n\n**Learn more:**\n\n*   [Caring for yourself at home](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/if-you-are-sick/caring-for-yourself-at-home.html) from the CDC\n*   [10 ways to manage respiratory symptoms at home](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/downloads/10Things.pdf) from the CDC\n*   [Information on breastfeeding if you have COVID-19](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/need-extra-precautions/pregnancy-breastfeeding.html) from the CDC\n*   [What is isolation, quarantine and self-observation](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19-chart-observation-isolation-quarantine_final.pdf)\n*   [What to do if you are diagnosed with COVID-19](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19_What-to-do-if-you-are-diagnosed-with-COVID-19_final.pdf)",
                "date": "2020-10-29"
            },
